******
[1] World
Date: Fri 15 Oct 2010
Source: BBC News [edited]
<http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-11551919>


The number of cases of a deadly disease has more than doubled in the
last decade, according to the World Health Organization (WHO). Dengue
outbreaks are now a major threat to global public health. The UN
health agency warned that unless countries act now then the situation
will only get worse.

The WHO has warned that the increased number and size of dengue
outbreaks in some countries in the Western Pacific region, as well as
cases recorded in previously unaffected areas, are signs that firmer
action cannot be delayed. The number of cases in the Western Pacific
Region has more than doubled over the past 10 years. There has been a
significant increase in many countries this year [2010] alone.

40 percent of the world's population are at risk of the disease, with
the majority living in the Asia Pacific region. Out of these 2.5
billion people, more than 70 percent live in Asia Pacific countries.
500 000 people hospitalised each year. Children are most at risk of
dying.

The increased number of outbreaks may be caused by a number of
factors; including higher temperatures and rainfall, which produce
perfect breeding conditions for the mosquitoes that carry the disease
[viruses]. Growing populations, particularly in cities, and greater
international travel by infected individuals could also explain the
rise. The WHO says there is as yet no clear evidence that the
increase in cases was due to global warming. But changes in climate
do affect mosquitoes which spread the disease [viruses].

At a local level eliminating breeding sites like water jars, building
sites, and discarded garbage is essential in reducing the number of
mosquitoes. But a concerted international effort is vital, with urban
planning and improving sanitation essential to reducing the number of
dengue cases.

[Byline: Ania Lichtarowicz]

