******
[2] Pakistan
Date: Sun 17 Oct 2010
Source: The Express Tribune, International Herald Tribune [edited]
<http://tribune.com.pk/story/63740/the-epidemic-that-wasnt/>


Health institutes are giving conflicting reports about the number of
patients diagnosed with dengue fever in the country. While
[Pakistan's] National Institute of Health (NIH), the primary
institute for testing blood samples, says no patient has yet tested
positive for the disease, ministry of health officials and doctors at
government-run hospitals tell a different story. They say scores of
patients have been diagnosed with dengue and that too by NIH. These
conflicting reports, at the very least, point to a lack of
coordination between government health institutions.

"We receive blood samples from all over the country, but so far, no
one has been diagnosed with the disease," claimed Dr Jaleel Kamran of
Epidemic Investigation Cell at NIH on Saturday [16 Oct 2010]. However
Dr Rashid Jooma, director general Ministry of Health, denied NIH's
claims. He said 2000 patients suspected of suffering dengue fever had
been reported from across the country, out of which 1000 had tested
positive. "Almost all of the cases reported positive for dengue were
tested by NIH," he added. "All test samples of suspected dengue fever
patients coming to hospital were sent to NIH for tests," Dr Mehmood
Jamal concurred, who is the executive director of Pakistan Institute
of Medical Sciences.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[This report is confusing. It cites confirmed dengue cases diagnosed
in 4 major hospitals with confirmation by the NIH, yet an official
report from the same NIH indicated that no dengue virus infections
have been confirmed. The situation is further complicated by a 17 Oct
2010 report from Chen Qi
(<http://www.dowell-netherlands.com/2010/10/six-more-die-of-dengue-fever.html>)
that stated that 6 people died of dengue virus infections in Karachi
during the last 24 hours, raising the death toll to 12. Provincial
Dengue Surveillance Cell head Dr Shakeel Malik said 5 people died of
dengue in September 2010, while 7 fell victim to the disease in
October [2010]. The 14 Oct 2010 edition of The Nation
(<http://www.nation.com.pk/pakistan-news-newspaper-daily-english-online/Regional/Islamabad/14-Oct-2010/NIH-confirms-1141-cases-of-dengue-fever>)
reported that NIH received blood samples of 2553 dengue-suspected
patients of which 1141 have been declared positive. This, and
previous reports from Pakistan, clearly indicate that dengue cases
have been occurring in Pakistan. Reporting may be complicated by
disruption of communications from dealing with the massive flooding
that occurred there recently. ProMED-mail would be interested in any
information that would resolve this apparent conflict in NIH
reporting. Providing timely diagnosis, care, treatment, and
prevention of dengue under the conditions inflicted by the recent
terrible flooding would be an extraordinarily difficult task.

Maps of Pakistan can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/pakistan_pol_2002.jpg>
and the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00tj>. - Mod.TY]

******
[3] Puerto Rico
Date: Sat 16 Oct 2010
Source: elnuevodia [in Spanish, trans. Corr.SB, summ. & edited]
<http://www.elnuevodia.com/siguecirculandoelvirusdeldengue-799301.html>


Although according to the US CDC report the numbers of suspected
cases of dengue appear to have fallen, in practice, it would seem
otherwise. According to the CDC, at week 38 (17-23 Sep 2010) 757
cases were reported, indicating a decrease compared to previous
weeks. However, cases continue to be above the epidemic threshold,
which means that the dengue epidemic is continuing. With another
confirmed death, the CDC has confirmed 27 fatalities. Although they
have not reported how many people have been infected with DHF, it was
noted that there are more than 28, the same figure as they gave last
week.

[Byline: Marga Pares Arroyo]

--
