******
[5] Cases in various countries: Malaysia, Philippines, Taiwan, Nepal,
India, Pakistan, Australia, Barbados, Martinique, Mexico, Brazil

- Malaysia: according to the Malaysian Health Ministry, a total of 37
419 dengue cases were reported in the country from January to 2 Oct
2010, an increase of 17 percent or 5411 cases compared with 32 008
cases recorded in the same period last year (2009). During the
period, 117 dengue deaths were reported, a surge of 65 percent or an
increase of 46 cases compared with the same period last year (2009).
The Malaysian government is researching on the possibility of using
genetically modified mosquitoes to control dengue
(<http://aglocojalurgemilang.blogspot.com/2010/10/dengue-death-cases-increases-by-65-in.html>).

- Philippines (Davao Oriental): 8 persons died of dengue fever in the
Caraga region (Davao Oriental region) while a total of 2369 cases
were admitted in different hospitals in the region from 1 Jan-8 Oct
2010, health officials reported Thursday (14 Oct 2010]. The number of
cases was 174 percent higher compared to 2009 when only 853 cases
were recorded
(<http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/282233/dengue-cases-rise-caraga?utm_medium=twitter>).

- Taiwan: a total of 111 new dengue fever cases originating in Taiwan
were reported during the week of 3 Oct 2010, setting a new single
week record, with most of the cases concentrated in southern Taiwan,
CDC Deputy Director-General Shih Wen-yi said at a news conference.
Shih also said all 4 serotypes of dengue virus have emerged
(<http://focustaiwan.tw/ShowNews/WebNews_Detail.aspx?Type=aSOC&ID=201010120025>).

- Nepal (Parsa): Out of many patients who came for treatment at
different hospitals in Birgunj (Parsa district), 8 have tested
positive for dengue disease (<http://newsmandu.com/story/183126/>).

- India (Delhi): the Municipal Corporation of Delhi, has officially
recorded 4244 cases with 7 fatalities as of 12 Oct 2010, 79 of them
in the last hours. The number now exceeds 3366 cases detected in
2006, a year in which 36 people died from the disease, although the
number affected could be higher since not all patients come to
hospitals and that the statistical system is weak
(<http://www.elconfidencial.com/ultima-hora/2010/10/personas-afectadas-brote-dengue-nueva-delhi-20101012-375741.html>).

- India (Tamil Nadu): According to Dr P Ramachandran, director of the
Institute of Child Health, 15 children with symptoms of dengue were
undergoing treatment at the hospital since the last 10 days. The
statistics from the Department of Public Health and Preventive
Medicine reveal that 21 dengue cases emerged from Tamil Nadu over the
past week with 10 of them from Chennai. From January through
September this year (2010), 986 dengue cases have been recorded in
Tamil Nadu
(<http://www.themedguru.com/20101012/newsfeature/15-children-hospitalized-dengue-chennai-86140925.html>).

- Pakistan (Lahore): more than 50 patients have tested positive for
dengue in Lahore, SAMAA TV reported Wednesday [13 Oct 2010]. The
Punjab Institute of Public Health has confirmed 37 patients dengue
positive
(<http://www.samaa.tv/News26525-Dengue_surfaces_in_Lahore.aspx>).

- Australia (Queensland): another 3 cases of dengue fever have been
recorded at Townsville in north Queensland, bringing the city's tally
to 13 since the start of 2010
(<http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/10/15/3039601.htm?utm_source=RoamMedia&utm_medium=twitter&utm_campaign=Queensland_Online>).

- Barbados: 321 cases of dengue fever with 3 reported deaths have
been confirmed, in comparison to 91 in 2009. The rise of dengue cases
was not restricted to Barbados, as there were 872 cases recorded in
the region this year up to July (2010), in comparison to 242 during
the same period last year (2009)
(<http://www.nationnews.com/index.php/articles/view/321-confirmed-cases-of-dengue/>).

- Martinique: Although the virus circulation is now moderate in most
municipalities in the south of Martinique, it still remains high in
some northern cities. Approximately 41 200 cases, clinically
suggestive, of dengue were reported in Martinique since the outbreak
began last February 2010, including 619 patients and 16 deaths
directly related to dengue
(<http://www.invs.sante.fr/surveillance/dengue/points_martinique/2010/pe_martinique_2010_24_dengue.pdf>).

- Mexico: there have been 365 dengue cases in Tamaulipas, 800 in
Nuevo Leon, and 500 in Veracruz states
(<http://laverdad.com.mx/desplegar_noticia.php?seccion=LOCAL¬a=56865>).

- Brazil (Parana): there have been 31 835 confirmed dengue cases in
Parana so far this year [2010]. There were 56 DHF cases and 94 cases
of dengue with complications. There were 8 dengue deaths
(<http://g1.globo.com/brasil/noticia/2010/10/parana-confirma-31835-casos-de-dengue-neste-ano.html>).

- Brazil (Mato Grosso): the state has registered 42 218 dengue cases
in January-14 Oct 2010, of which 900 were considered serious cases.
There have been 60 deaths, 50 confirmed as dengue and 10 under
investigation. During the same period last year (2009), there were 40
161 total cases
(<http://oglobo.globo.com/pais/noblat/posts/2010/10/16/mt-ja-registra-mais-de-42-mil-casos-de-dengue-este-ano-333070.asp>).

- Brazil (Goias): up to 9 Oct 2010, 98 653 dengue cases were
registered with 65 deaths, 39 of dengue with complications and 26 of
DHF. Compared with the same period last year [2009], there is an
increase of 80.8 percent
(<http://www.noticiasdegoias.go.gov.br/index.php?idMateria=88655>).

